279 /* Large file support */
280 /* Note that CONFIG_LFS=y forces bbox to be built with all common ops
281  * (stat, lseek etc) mapped to "largefile" variants by libc.
282  * Practically it means that open() automatically has O_LARGEFILE added
283  * and all filesize/file_offset parameters and struct members are "large"
284  * (in today's world - signed 64bit). For full support of large files,
285  * we need a few helper #defines (below) and careful use of off_t
286  * instead of int/ssize_t. No lseek64(), O_LARGEFILE etc necessary */
287 #if ENABLE_LFS
288 /* CONFIG_LFS is on */
289 # if ULONG_MAX > 0xffffffff
290 /* "long" is long enough on this system */
291 typedef unsigned long uoff_t;
292 # define XATOOFF(a) xatoul_range((a), 0, LONG_MAX)
293 /* usage: sz = BB_STRTOOFF(s, NULL, 10); if (errno || sz < 0) die(); */
294 # define BB_STRTOOFF bb_strtoul
295 # define STRTOOFF strtoul
296 /* usage: printf("size: %"OFF_FMT"d (%"OFF_FMT"x)\n", sz, sz); */
297 # define OFF_FMT "l"
298 # else
299 /* "long" is too short, need "long long" */
300 typedef unsigned long long uoff_t;
301 # define XATOOFF(a) xatoull_range((a), 0, LLONG_MAX)
302 # define BB_STRTOOFF bb_strtoull
303 # define STRTOOFF strtoull
304 # define OFF_FMT "ll"
305 # endif
306 #else
307 /* CONFIG_LFS is off */
308 /* sizeof(off_t) == sizeof(long).
309  * May or may not be == sizeof(int). If it is, use xatoi_positive()
310  * and bb_strtou() instead of xatoul_range() and bb_strtoul().
311  * Even if sizeof(off_t) == sizeof(int), off_t is typedef'ed to long anyway.
312  * gcc will throw warnings on printf("%d", off_t)... Have to use %ld etc.
313  */
314 # if UINT_MAX == ULONG_MAX
315 typedef unsigned long uoff_t;
316 # define XATOOFF(a) xatoi_positive(a)
317 # define BB_STRTOOFF bb_strtou
318 # define STRTOOFF strtol
319 # define OFF_FMT "l"
320 # else
321 typedef unsigned long uoff_t;
322 # define XATOOFF(a) xatoul_range((a), 0, LONG_MAX)
323 # define BB_STRTOOFF bb_strtoul
324 # define STRTOOFF strtol
325 # define OFF_FMT "l"
326 # endif
327 #endif
328 /* scary. better ideas? (but do *test* them first!) */
329 #define OFF_T_MAX ((off_t)~((off_t)1 << (sizeof(off_t)*8-1)))
330 /* Users report bionic to use 32-bit off_t even if LARGEFILE support is requested.
331  * On musl, !ENABLE_LFS on 32-bit arches thinks that off_t is 32-bit.
332  * We misdetected that. Don't let it build:
333  */
334 struct BUG_off_t_size_is_misdetected {
335  char BUG_off_t_size_is_misdetected[sizeof(off_t) == sizeof(uoff_t) ? 1 : -1];
336 };

373  * and reduced binary size by a few kilobytes) like:
374  * ash.c: extern struct globals *const ash_ptr_to_globals;

421 /* After v = xrealloc_vector(v, SHIFT, idx) it's ok to use
422  * at least v[idx] and v[idx+1], for all idx values.
423  * SHIFT specifies how many new elements are added (1:2, 2:4, ..., 8:256...)
424  * when all elements are used up. New elements are zeroed out.
425  * xrealloc_vector(v, SHIFT, idx) *MUST* be called with consecutive IDXs -
426  * skipping an index is a bad bug - it may miss a realloc!
427  */
428 #define xrealloc_vector(vector, shift, idx) \
429  xrealloc_vector_helper((vector), (sizeof((vector)[0]) << 8) + (shift), (idx))
430 void* xrealloc_vector_helper(void *vector, unsigned sizeof_and_shift, int idx) FAST_FUNC;

479  FILEUTILS_UPDATE = 1 << 14, /* -u */

486 /* How many bits in FILEUTILS_CP_OPTSTR? */

488 
489  FILEUTILS_RMDEST = 1 << (19 - !ENABLE_SELINUX), /* cp --remove-destination */
490  /* bit 18 skipped for "cp --parents" */
491  FILEUTILS_REFLINK = 1 << (20 - !ENABLE_SELINUX), /* cp --reflink=auto */
492  FILEUTILS_REFLINK_ALWAYS = 1 << (21 - !ENABLE_SELINUX), /* cp --reflink[=always] */

590 enum {
591  /* bb_signals(BB_FATAL_SIGS, handler) catches all signals which
592  * otherwise would kill us, except for those resulting from bugs:
593  * SIGSEGV, SIGILL, SIGFPE.
594  * Other fatal signals not included (TODO?):
595  * SIGBUS Bus error (bad memory access)
596  * SIGPOLL Pollable event. Synonym of SIGIO
597  * SIGPROF Profiling timer expired
598  * SIGSYS Bad argument to routine
599  * SIGTRAP Trace/breakpoint trap
600  *
601  * The only known arch with some of these sigs not fitting
602  * into 32 bits is parisc (SIGXCPU=33, SIGXFSZ=34, SIGSTKFLT=36).
603  * Dance around with long long to guard against that...
604  */
605  BB_FATAL_SIGS = (int)(0
606  + (1LL << SIGHUP)
607  + (1LL << SIGINT)
608  + (1LL << SIGTERM)
609  + (1LL << SIGPIPE) // Write to pipe with no readers
610  + (1LL << SIGQUIT) // Quit from keyboard
611  + (1LL << SIGABRT) // Abort signal from abort(3)
612  + (1LL << SIGALRM) // Timer signal from alarm(2)
613  + (1LL << SIGVTALRM) // Virtual alarm clock
614  + (1LL << SIGXCPU) // CPU time limit exceeded
615  + (1LL << SIGXFSZ) // File size limit exceeded
616  + (1LL << SIGUSR1) // Yes kids, these are also fatal!
617  + (1LL << SIGUSR2)
618  + 0),
619 };

1285 /* Helpers for daemonization.
1286  *
1287  * bb_daemonize(flags) = daemonize, does not compile on NOMMU
1288  *
1289  * bb_daemonize_or_rexec(flags, argv) = daemonizes on MMU (and ignores argv),
1290  * rexec's itself on NOMMU with argv passed as command line.
1291  * Thus bb_daemonize_or_rexec may cause your <applet>_main() to be re-executed
1292  * from the start. (It will detect it and not reexec again second time).
1293  * You have to audit carefully that you don't do something twice as a result
1294  * (opening files/sockets, parsing config files etc...)!
1295  *
1296  * Both of the above will redirect fd 0,1,2 to /dev/null and drop ctty
1297  * (will do setsid()).
1298  *
1299  * fork_or_rexec(argv) = bare-bones fork on MMU,
1300  * "vfork + re-exec ourself" on NOMMU. No fd redirection, no setsid().
1301  * On MMU ignores argv.
1302  *
1303  * Helper for network daemons in foreground mode:
1304  *
1305  * bb_sanitize_stdio() = make sure that fd 0,1,2 are opened by opening them
1306  * to /dev/null if they are not.
1307  */
1308 enum {
1309  DAEMON_CHDIR_ROOT = 1 << 0,
1310  DAEMON_DEVNULL_STDIO = 1 << 1,
1311  DAEMON_CLOSE_EXTRA_FDS = 1 << 2,
1312  DAEMON_ONLY_SANITIZE = 1 << 3, /* internal use */
1313  //DAEMON_DOUBLE_FORK = 1 << 4, /* double fork to avoid controlling tty */
1314 };
1315 #if BB_MMU
1316  enum { re_execed = 0 };
1317 # define fork_or_rexec(argv) xfork()
1318 # define bb_daemonize_or_rexec(flags, argv) bb_daemonize_or_rexec(flags)
1319 # define bb_daemonize(flags) bb_daemonize_or_rexec(flags, bogus)
1320 #else
1321  extern bool re_execed;
1322  /* Note: re_exec() and fork_or_rexec() do argv[0][0] |= 0x80 on NOMMU!
1323  * _Parent_ needs to undo it if it doesn't want to have argv[0] mangled.

1325  void re_exec(char **argv) NORETURN FAST_FUNC;

1357 /* BSD-derived getopt() functions require that optind be set to 1 in
1358  * order to reset getopt() state. This used to be generally accepted
1359  * way of resetting getopt(). However, glibc's getopt()
1360  * has additional getopt() state beyond optind (specifically, glibc
1361  * extensions such as '+' and '-' at the start of the string), and requires
1362  * that optind be set to zero to reset its state. BSD-derived versions
1363  * of getopt() misbehaved if optind is set to 0 in order to reset getopt(),
1364  * and glibc's getopt() used to coredump if optind is set 1 in order
1365  * to reset getopt().
1366  * Then BSD introduced additional variable "optreset" which should be
1367  * set to 1 in order to reset getopt(). Sigh. Standards, anyone?
1368  *
1369  * By ~2008, OpenBSD 3.4 was changed to survive glibc-like optind = 0
1370  * (to interpret it as if optreset was set).
1371  */
1372 #if 1 /*def __GLIBC__*/
1373 #define GETOPT_RESET() (optind = 0)
1374 #else /* BSD style */
1375 #define GETOPT_RESET() (optind = 1)
1376 #endif

1629 /*
1630  * Config file parser
1631  */
1632 enum {
1633  PARSE_COLLAPSE = 0x00010000, // treat consecutive delimiters as one
1634  PARSE_TRIM = 0x00020000, // trim leading and trailing delimiters
1635 // TODO: COLLAPSE and TRIM seem to always go in pair
1636  PARSE_GREEDY = 0x00040000, // last token takes entire remainder of the line
1637  PARSE_MIN_DIE = 0x00100000, // die if < min tokens found
1638  // keep a copy of current line
1639  PARSE_KEEP_COPY = 0x00200000 * ENABLE_FEATURE_CROND_D,
1640  PARSE_EOL_COMMENTS = 0x00400000, // comments are recognized even if they aren't the first char
1641  PARSE_ALT_COMMENTS = 0x00800000, // delim[0] and delim[1] are two different allowed comment chars
1642  // (so far, delim[0] will only work as comment char for full-line comment)
1643  // (IOW: it works as if PARSE_EOL_COMMENTS is not set. sysctl applet is okay with this)
1644  PARSE_WS_COMMENTS = 0x01000000, // comments are recognized even if there is whitespace before
1645  // ("line start><space><tab><space>#comment" is also comment, not only "line start>#comment")
1646  // NORMAL is:
1647  // * remove leading and trailing delimiters and collapse
1648  // multiple delimiters into one
1649  // * warn and continue if less than mintokens delimiters found
1650  // * grab everything into last token
1651  // * comments are recognized even if they aren't the first char
1652  PARSE_NORMAL = PARSE_COLLAPSE | PARSE_TRIM | PARSE_GREEDY | PARSE_EOL_COMMENTS,
1653 };

1730 /* setup_environment:
1731  * if SETUP_ENV_CHDIR:
1732  * if cd(pw->pw_dir): ok: else if SETUP_ENV_TO_TMP: cd(/tmp) else: cd(/) or die
1733  * if SETUP_ENV_CLEARENV: cd(pw->pw_dir), clear environment, then set
1734  * TERM=(old value)
1735  * USER=pw->pw_name, LOGNAME=pw->pw_name
1736  * PATH=bb_default_[root_]path
1737  * HOME=pw->pw_dir
1738  * SHELL=shell
1739  * else if SETUP_ENV_CHANGEENV | SETUP_ENV_CHANGEENV_LOGNAME:
1740  * if not root (if pw->pw_uid != 0) or if SETUP_ENV_CHANGEENV_LOGNAME:
1741  * USER=pw->pw_name, LOGNAME=pw->pw_name
1742  * HOME=pw->pw_dir
1743  * SHELL=shell
1744  * else does nothing
1745  *
1746  * NB: CHANGEENV and CLEARENV use setenv() - this leaks memory!
1747  * If setup_environment() is used is vforked child, this leaks memory _in parent too_!
1748  */
1749 #define SETUP_ENV_CHANGEENV (1 << 0)
1750 #define SETUP_ENV_CHANGEENV_LOGNAME (1 << 1)
1751 #define SETUP_ENV_CLEARENV (1 << 2)

1893  * We want it big enough to be able to contain
1894  * cursor position sequence "ESC [ 9999 ; 9999 R"

1898 /* Note: fd may be in blocking or non-blocking mode, both make sense.
1899  * For one, less uses non-blocking mode.
1900  * Only the first read syscall inside read_key may block indefinitely
1901  * (unless fd is in non-blocking mode),
1902  * subsequent reads will time out after a few milliseconds.
1903  * Return of -1 means EOF or error (errno == 0 on EOF).
1904  * Nonzero errno is not preserved across the call:
1905  * if there was no error, errno will be cleared to 0.
1906  * buffer[0] is used as a counter of buffered chars and must be 0
1907  * on first call.
1908  * timeout:
1909  * -2: do not poll(-1) for input - read() it, return on EAGAIN at once
1910  * -1: poll(-1) (i.e. block even on NONBLOCKed fd)
1911  * >=0: poll() for TIMEOUT milliseconds, return -1/EAGAIN on timeout
1912  */
1913 int64_t read_key(int fd, char *buffer, int timeout) FAST_FUNC;
1914 /* This version loops on EINTR: */
1915 int64_t safe_read_key(int fd, char *buffer, int timeout) FAST_FUNC;

2441 /* We save ~500 bytes on isdigit alone.
2442  * BTW, x86 likes (unsigned char) cast more than (unsigned). */
2443 
2444 /* These work the same for ASCII and Unicode,
2445  * assuming no one asks "is this a *Unicode* letter?" using isalpha(letter) */
2446 #define isascii(a) ((unsigned char)(a) <= 0x7f)
2447 #define isdigit(a) ((unsigned char)((a) - '0') <= 9)
2448 #define isupper(a) ((unsigned char)((a) - 'A') <= ('Z' - 'A'))
2449 #define islower(a) ((unsigned char)((a) - 'a') <= ('z' - 'a'))
2450 #define isalpha(a) ((unsigned char)(((a)|0x20) - 'a') <= ('z' - 'a'))
2451 #define isblank(a) ({ unsigned char bb__isblank = (a); bb__isblank == ' ' || bb__isblank == '\t'; })
2452 #define iscntrl(a) ({ unsigned char bb__iscntrl = (a); bb__iscntrl < ' ' || bb__iscntrl == 0x7f; })
2453 /* In POSIX/C locale isspace is only these chars: "\t\n\v\f\r" and space.
2454  * "\t\n\v\f\r" happen to have ASCII codes 9,10,11,12,13.
2455  */
2456 #define isspace(a) ({ unsigned char bb__isspace = (a) - 9; bb__isspace == (' ' - 9) || bb__isspace <= (13 - 9); })
2457 // Unsafe wrt NUL: #define ispunct(a) (strchr("!\"#$%&'()*+,-./:;<=>?@[\\]^_`{|}~", (a)) != NULL)
2458 #define ispunct(a) (strchrnul("!\"#$%&'()*+,-./:;<=>?@[\\]^_`{|}~", (a))[0])
2459 // Bigger code: #define isalnum(a) ({ unsigned char bb__isalnum = (a) - '0'; bb__isalnum <= 9 || ((bb__isalnum - ('A' - '0')) & 0xdf) <= 25; })
2460 #define isalnum(a) bb_ascii_isalnum(a)
2461 static ALWAYS_INLINE int bb_ascii_isalnum(unsigned char a)
2462 {
2463  unsigned char b = a - '0';
2464  if (b <= 9)
2465  return (b <= 9);
2466  b = (a|0x20) - 'a';
2467  return b <= 'z' - 'a';
2468 }
2469 #define isxdigit(a) bb_ascii_isxdigit(a)
2470 static ALWAYS_INLINE int bb_ascii_isxdigit(unsigned char a)
2471 {
2472  unsigned char b = a - '0';
2473  if (b <= 9)
2474  return (b <= 9);
2475  b = (a|0x20) - 'a';
2476  return b <= 'f' - 'a';
2477 }
2478 #define toupper(a) bb_ascii_toupper(a)
2479 static ALWAYS_INLINE unsigned char bb_ascii_toupper(unsigned char a)
2480 {
2481  unsigned char b = a - 'a';
2482  if (b <= ('z' - 'a'))
2483  a -= 'a' - 'A';
2484  return a;
2485 }
2486 #define tolower(a) bb_ascii_tolower(a)
2487 static ALWAYS_INLINE unsigned char bb_ascii_tolower(unsigned char a)
2488 {
2489  unsigned char b = a - 'A';
2490  if (b <= ('Z' - 'A'))
2491  a += 'a' - 'A';
2492  return a;
2493 }
